{
  "@context": "https://www.openphar.org/ontology/context/pharmacopoeia.jsonld",
  "@id": "https://www.openphar.org/data/jp/chemicals/ethacridine-lactate",
  "@type": "ChemicalDrugMonograph",
  "prefLabel": {
    "en": "Ethacridine Lactate",
    "ja": "アクリノール水和物"
  },
  "monographId": "JP18-ethacridine-lactate",
  "publisher": "JP",
  "status": "Official",
  "version": "18",
  "molecularFormula": "C15H15N3O.C3H6O3.H2O",
  "molecularWeight": 361.39,
  "appearance": {
    "en": "Acrinol Hydrate occurs as a yellow crystalline powder. It is sparingly soluble in water, in methanol and in ethanol (99.5). Melting point: about 2459C (with decomposition). The pH of a solution of Acrinol Hydrate (1 in 100) is between 5.5 and 7.0."
  },
  "testSpecification": [
    {
      "@type": "IdentificationSpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Identification"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Identification",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Determine the absorption spectrum of a solution of Acrinol Hydrate (3 in 250,000) as directed under ‌JP XVIII Official Monographs / Acrinol and Zinc Oxide Oil 415 Ultraviolet-visible Spectrophotometry <2.24>, and compare the spectrum with the Reference Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of absorption at the same wave-lengths. Determine the infrared absorption spectrum of Acrinol Hydrate as directed in the potassium bromide disk method under Infrared Spectrophotometry <2.25>, and com-pare the spectrum with the Reference Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of absorption at the same wave numbers. To 5 mL of a solution of Acrinol Hydrate (1 in 100) add 5 mL of dilute sulfuric acid, shake well, allow to stand for about 10 minutes at room temperature, and filter: the fil-trate responds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> for lactate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "PuritySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Purity"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Purity",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Chloride <1.03>—Dissolve 1.0 g of Acrinol Hy-drate in 80 mL of water by warming on a water bath, cool, and add 10 mL of sodium hydroxide TS and water to make 100 mL. Shake well, allow to stand for 30 minutes, filter, to 40 mL of the filtrate add 7 mL of dilute nitric acid and water to make 50 mL, and perform the test using this solution as the test solution. Prepare 50 mL of the control solution with 4 mL of sodium hydroxide TS, 7 mL of dilute nitric acid, 0.30 mL of 0.01 mol/L hydrochloric acid VS and sufficient water (not more than 0.026z). Heavy metals <1.07>—Proceed with 1.0 g of Acrinol Hydrate according to Method 2, and perform the test. Pre- System suitability— Test for required detectability: Confirm that the peak area of acrinol obtained with 10 mL of the standard solution (2) is equivalent to 7 to 13z of that with 10 mL of the standard solution (1). System performance: When the procedure is run with 10 mL of the standard solution (1) under the above operating conditions, the number of theoretical plates and the symme-try factor of the peak of acrinol are not less than 5000 and not more than 2.0, respectively. System repeatability: When the test is repeated 6 times with 10 mL of the standard solution (1) under the above operating conditions, the relative standard deviation of the peak area of acrinol is not more than 1.5z. Water <2.48> 4.5 – 5.5z (0.2 g, volumetric titration, direct titration) Residue on ignition <2.44> Not more than 0.1z (1 g)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "AssaySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Assay"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Assay",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "Weigh accurately about 0.27 g of Acrinol Hydrate, dissolve in 5 mL of formic acid, add 60 mL of a mixture of acetic anhydride and acetic acid (100) (1:1), and titrate <2.50> immediately with 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid VS (potentio-metric titration). Perform a blank determination in the same manner, and make any necessary correction. Each mL of 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid VS ＝ 34.34 mg of C H N O.C H O pare the control solution with 2.0 mL of Standard Lead So- 15 15 3 3 6 3 lution (not more than 20 ppm). Volatile fatty acids—Dissolve 0.5 g of Acrinol Hy-drate in a mixture of 20 mL of water and 5 mL of dilute sul-furic acid, shake well, filter, and heat the filtrate: no odor of volatile fatty acids is perceptible. Related substances—Dissolve 10 mg of Acrinol Hy-drate in 25 mL of the mobile phase, and use this solution as the sample solution. Pipet 1 mL of the sample solution, add the mobile phase to make exactly 100 mL, and use this solu-tion as the standard solution (1). Pipet 1 mL of the standard solution (1), add the mobile phase to make exactly 10 mL, and use this solution as the standard solution (2). Perform the test with exactly 10 mL each of the sample solution and standard solutions (1) and (2) as directed under Liquid Chro-matography <2.01> according to the following conditions, and determine each peak area by the automatic integration method: the area of the peak other than acrinol obtained from the sample solution is not larger than 3 times the peak area of acrinol from the standard solution (2), and the total area of the peaks other than acrinol from the sample solu-tion is not larger than the peak area of acrinol from the standard solution (1). Operating conditions— Detector: An ultraviolet absorption photometer (wave-length: 268 nm). Column: A stainless steel column 4.6 mm in inside diame-ter and 25 cm in length, packed with octadecylsilanized silica gel for liquid chromatography (5 mm in particle diameter). Column temperature: A constant temperature of about 259C. Mobile phase: Dissolve 7.8 g of sodium dihydrogen phos-phate in 900 mL of water, adjust to pH 2.8 with phosphoric acid, and add water to make 1000 mL. To 700 mL of this solution add 300 mL of acetonitrile for liquid chromatogra-phy, and add 1.0 g of sodium 1-octanesulfonate to dissolve. Flow rate: Adjust so that the retention time of acrinol is about 15 minutes. Time span of measurement: About 3 times as long as the retention time of acrinol, beginning after the solvent peak."
      }
    }
  ],
  "storageConditions": {
    "en": "Containers—Tight containers. Storage—Light-resistant."
  }
}